<subSubSection id="DCF9AAB63E3D4F0EFF1C3821FECDFE81" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="11" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="945CF93D3E3D4F0DFF1C3821FE13FAD8" blockId="9.[156,771,1145,1290]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis id="A697252F3E3D4F0DFF1C3821FEB8FB5D" box="[156,268,1146,1167]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Dorsal interfrontal setae and median frontal furrow absent. Tergites (especially tergite 2) bare or with relatively small setae. Hind tibia lacking anterodorsal rows of enlarged setae. Mid and hind tarsal claws not bifurcate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="945CF93D3E3D4F0DFF1C3979FEE3FA03" blockId="9.[156,772,1314,1612]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis id="A697252F3E3D4F0DFF1C3979FE8DFAEA" box="[156,313,1314,1336]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Included taxa</emphasis>
. Subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="53E382BE3E3D4F0DFE3F3979FDF7FAE5" authorityName="Brues" authorityYear="1904" box="[447,579,1314,1335]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Melaloncha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A697252F3E3D4F0DFE3F3979FDF7FAE5" box="[447,579,1314,1335]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Melaloncha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
includes most of the species of the genus. Some of these can be organized into informal groups, based partly on the analysis of phylogenetically informative characters of higher taxa (
<figureCitation id="0CD8E5B83E3D4F0DFEB339C6FE35FA61" box="[307,385,1437,1459]" captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="7.[820,898,943,962]" captionTargetBox="[823,1431,202,911]" captionTargetId="graphics-343@7.[824,1403,489,912]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 18. Cladogram of phylogenetic relationships within Melaloncha." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5439611" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5439611/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
), and partly on other characters, discussed below.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="945CF93D3E3D4F0DFF343981FDDFF99E" blockId="9.[156,772,1314,1612]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis id="A697252F3E3D4F0DFF343981FEA7FA22" box="[180,275,1498,1520]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Group I.</emphasis>
These species probably do not form a monophyletic group; rather they are a grade that include 
<emphasis id="A697252F3E3D4F0DFF1C3A43FF0EF9FF" box="[156,186,1560,1581]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">M.</emphasis>
(
<taxonomicName id="53E382BE3E3D4F0DFF493A4CFEF9F9FE" authorityName="Brues" authorityYear="1904" box="[201,333,1559,1580]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Melaloncha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A697252F3E3D4F0DFF493A4CFEF9F9FE" box="[201,333,1559,1580]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Melaloncha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) species that lack thickened foretarsal claws. Within Group I are the following:
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="945CF93D3E3D4F0DFF2C3A3FFD49F965" blockId="9.[164,772,1636,1903]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
(i) 
<taxonomicName id="53E382BE3E3D4F0DFF503A3EFEC2F9AB" authorityName="Borgmeier" authorityYear="1934" box="[208,374,1636,1658]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Melaloncha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctifrons">
<emphasis id="A697252F3E3D4F0DFF503A3EFEC2F9AB" box="[208,374,1636,1658]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">M. punctifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group. Includes 
<taxonomicName id="53E382BE3E3D4F0DFDDD3A3EFEFCF94B" authority="Borgmeier" authorityName="Borgmeier" authorityYear="1934" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Melaloncha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctifrons">
<emphasis id="A697252F3E3D4F0DFDDD3A3EFCB0F9AB" box="[605,772,1636,1658]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">M. punctifrons</emphasis>
Borgmeier
</taxonomicName>
and one undescribed species. Both have lost the frontal setae, except those of the vertex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="945CF93D3E3D4F0DFF243A9BFECFF8BD" blockId="9.[164,772,1636,1903]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
(ii) 
<taxonomicName id="53E382BE3E3D4F0DFF503A9AFEE7F907" authorityName="Borgmeier" authorityYear="1959" box="[208,339,1728,1750]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Melaloncha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="digitalis">
<emphasis id="A697252F3E3D4F0DFF503A9AFEE7F907" box="[208,339,1728,1750]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">M. digitalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group. Containing 
<taxonomicName id="53E382BE3E3D4F0DFDB73A9AFEA5F927" authority="Borgmeier" authorityName="Borgmeier" authorityYear="1959" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Melaloncha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="digitalis">
<emphasis id="A697252F3E3D4F0DFDB73A9AFD0EF907" box="[567,698,1728,1750]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">M. digitalis</emphasis>
Borgmeier
</taxonomicName>
and a few undescribed species, this group is characterized by ventral interfrontal setae that are vertically below the fronto-orbital setae, as well as ovipositors that are dorsally curved and densely setose.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="945CF93D3E3D4F0DFCB43F74FB5DFC2F" blockId="9.[820,1436,815,1021]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
(iii) Miscellaneous Group I species. This assemblage includes 
<taxonomicName id="53E382BE3E3D4F0DFC513F15FB5CFCB1" authority="Borgmeier" authorityName="Borgmeier" authorityYear="1934" box="[977,1256,845,867]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Melaloncha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cuspidata">
<emphasis id="A697252F3E3D4F0DFC513F15FBD0FCB0" box="[977,1124,845,867]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">M. cuspidata</emphasis>
Borgmeier
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="53E382BE3E3D4F0DFB763F15FC1DFC50" authority="Borgmeier" authorityName="Borgmeier" authorityYear="1959" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Melaloncha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flava">
<emphasis id="A697252F3E3D4F0DFB763F15FAE6FCB0" box="[1270,1362,845,867]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">M. flava</emphasis>
Borgmeier
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="53E382BE3E3D4F0DFC343F36FB63FC50" authority="Borgmeier" authorityName="Borgmeier" authorityYear="1938" box="[948,1239,876,898]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Melaloncha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plaumanni">
<emphasis id="A697252F3E3D4F0DFC343F36FBE3FC53" box="[948,1111,876,898]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">M. plaumanni</emphasis>
Borgmeier
</taxonomicName>
, and at least two undescribed species. If 
<bibRefCitation id="F07284CC3E3D4F0DFBFD3FD0FAFCFC73" author="Borgmeier T" box="[1149,1352,907,929]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" pagination="1 - 172" refId="ref30486" refString="Borgmeier T. 1971. Further studies on phorid flies, mainly of the Neotropical Region (Diptera, Phoridae). Studia Entomologica 14: 1 - 172." type="journal article" year="1971">Borgmeier (1971)</bibRefCitation>
is correct about the 
<typeStatus id="4B58479F3E3D4F0DFBBC3FF1FBD9FC6D" box="[1084,1133,938,959]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">type</typeStatus>
species of the genus, 
<taxonomicName id="53E382BE3E3D4F0DFCE83F92FC41FC0F" authorityName="Brues" authorityYear="1904" box="[872,1013,968,990]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Melaloncha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pulchella">
<emphasis id="A697252F3E3D4F0DFCE83F92FC41FC0F" box="[872,1013,968,990]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">M. pulchella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, being closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="53E382BE3E3D4F0DFAB43F92FC06FC2E" authorityName="Borgmeier" authorityYear="1938" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Melaloncha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plaumanni">
<emphasis id="A697252F3E3D4F0DFAB43F92FC06FC2E" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">M. plaumanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, it would also belong here.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="945CF93D3E3D4F0DFCCC3843FA2CFB15" blockId="9.[820,1435,1047,1223]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis id="A697252F3E3D4F0DFCCC3843FC02FBFF" box="[844,950,1048,1069]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Group II.</emphasis>
This is another probably nonmonophyletic group whose species have thickened claws, but lack the three-pronged process on intersegment 7–8 (thus excluding them from the 
<taxonomicName id="53E382BE3E3D4F0DFBD4382FFB55FB5A" authorityName="Borgmeier" authorityYear="1938" box="[1108,1249,1139,1161]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Melaloncha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ungulata">
<emphasis id="A697252F3E3D4F0DFBD4382FFB55FB5A" box="[1108,1249,1139,1161]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">M. ungulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group) and lack wing vein R 
<subScript id="0867FB783E3D4F0DFC5838C0FC45FB7B" attach="left" box="[984,1009,1179,1193]" fontSize="6" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">2+3</subScript>
(thus excluding them from the 
<taxonomicName id="53E382BE3E3D4F0DFCB438EAFC1EFB14" authorityName="Borgmeier" authorityYear="1934" box="[820,938,1201,1222]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Melaloncha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="furcata">
<emphasis id="A697252F3E3D4F0DFCB438EAFC1EFB14" box="[820,938,1201,1222]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">M. furcata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group). Within Group II are the following:
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="945CF93D3E3D4F0DFCB438BAFAE7FA81" blockId="9.[820,1436,1249,1670]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
(iv) 
<taxonomicName id="53E382BE3E3D4F0DFCE638B9FBB6FB24" box="[870,1026,1249,1271]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Melaloncha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cingulatus">
<emphasis id="A697252F3E3D4F0DFCE638B9FBB6FB24" box="[870,1026,1249,1271]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">M. cingulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group. Besides 
<taxonomicName id="53E382BE3E3D4F0DFB3938B9FC13FAC4" authority="Borgmeier" authorityName="Borgmeier" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Melaloncha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cingulatus">
<emphasis id="A697252F3E3D4F0DFB3938B9FAE1FB24" box="[1209,1365,1249,1271]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">M. cingulatus</emphasis>
Borgmeier
</taxonomicName>
and possibly 
<taxonomicName id="53E382BE3E3D4F0DFBCD395AFAD4FAC4" authority="Borgmeier" authorityName="Borgmeier" authorityYear="1934" box="[1101,1376,1280,1302]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Melaloncha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lamellata">
<emphasis id="A697252F3E3D4F0DFBCD395AFB6AFAC7" box="[1101,1246,1280,1302]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">M. lamellata</emphasis>
Borgmeier
</taxonomicName>
, contains at least six undescribed species. All have ventral, cercus-like lobes on the ovipositor.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="945CF93D3E3D4F0DFCBC3907FB02FA1C" blockId="9.[820,1436,1249,1670]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">(v) Unnamed species group. At least three undescribed species belong in this group, united by a distinctive ovipositor structure and a fore tibia with a well developed flange.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="945CF93D3E3D4F0DFCB4398CFBE4F954" blockId="9.[820,1436,1249,1670]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
